Here are both approaches for .NET MAUI Shell navigation with `IQueryAttributable`.

## 1. Passing a simple string (product ID)

**Navigate from ProductListPage:**

```csharp
// In your ProductListPage code-behind or VM
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync($"{nameof(ProductDetailsPage)}?productId={product.Id}");
}
```

## 2. Passing a complex object

Shell navigation supports passing full objects via a dictionary overload:

```csharp
async void OnProductSelected(Product product)
{
    var navParams = new Dictionary<string, object>
    {
        { "product", product }
    };
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), navParams);
}
```

## Receiving both on the ViewModel

Implement `IQueryAttributable` on your ViewModel to handle **either** scenario in one place:

```csharp
public class ProductDetailsViewModel : ObservableObject, IQueryAttributable
{
    private readonly IProductService _productService;

    public ProductDetailsViewModel(IProductService productService)
    {
        _productService = productService;
    }

    [ObservableProperty]
    private Product? _product;

    public void ApplyQueryAttributes(IDictionary<string, object> query)
    {
        // Approach 2: full object passed directly
        if (query.TryGetValue("product", out var obj) && obj is Product product)
        {
            Product = product;
        }
        // Approach 1: only the ID was passed — load from a service
        else if (query.TryGetValue("productId", out var raw)
                 && raw?.ToString() is string id)
        {
            LoadProduct(id);
        }
    }

    private async void LoadProduct(string id)
    {
        Product = await _productService.GetProductByIdAsync(id);
    }
}
```

## Route registration & page wiring

```csharp
// In AppShell.xaml.cs or MauiProgram.cs
Routing.RegisterRoute(nameof(ProductDetailsPage), typeof(ProductDetailsPage));

// In MauiProgram.cs — register DI
builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsPage>();
builder.Services.AddTransient<ProductDetailsViewModel>();
```

```csharp
// ProductDetailsPage.xaml.cs
public ProductDetailsPage(ProductDetailsViewModel vm)
{
    InitializeComponent();
    BindingContext = vm;
}
```

**Key points:**

- **Simple values** — append to the URI as query-string params; they arrive as `string`.
- **Complex objects** — use the `Dictionary<string, object>` overload; they arrive as their original type, no serialization needed.
- `ApplyQueryAttributes` is called automatically by Shell before the page appears, so you can handle both cases in a single method.
